1 Log likelihood

a) Plot

Plot the log likelihood function as in slide 19.

# Note: theta represents the probability of success
logL <- function(theta){60*log(theta)+508*log(1-theta)} #Simplified/proportional likelihood
logL.exact <- function(theta){dbinom(60, 568, theta, log=T)} #Exact likelihood
curve(logL.exact, from = 0, to = 0.25)

# A prettier plot:
curve(logL.exact, from = 0, to = 0.25, ylim = c(-50,0), las=1, 
      xlab=expression(paste('Prevalence (',theta,')')), ylab='log(L)')

# Mathematical expressions can be included in the plot title or axis labels.
# For more information, see ?plotmath or run the demo with demo(plotmath).
# xlab can be written as expression(paste(Prevalence~(theta))
# paste() will take multiple elements as inputs and concatenate those inputs into a single string.

b) Max likelihood

Find θ so that the log likelihood is maximized.

## Use optim
optim(0.1, logL, method="CG", control=list(fnscale=-1))
optim(0.1, logL, method="Brent", lower=0.01, upper=0.25, control=list(fnscale=-1))
optim(0.1, logL, method="L-BFGS-B", lower=0.01, upper=0.99, control=list(fnscale=-1))

Functions

If a specific task is desired but there is no such predefined function in R, use user-defined functions.

  • fname <- function (arg1, arg2, …) statement
    • arg1, arg2 are the input variables
    • statement is the body of the function, usually enclosed within braces {} for a grouped statement
#Example
xsq <- function(x) x^2
xsq(5)
## [1] 25

Optim

Minimize (or maximize) a function over the parameter space | Youtube tutorial

  • optim(par, fn, lower, upper, method)
    • par … the initial values for the parameters to be optimized over
    • fn … the function to be optimized
    • lower, upper … the lower and upper bound of the parameters to be optimized over method select the optimization algorithm
    • add control=(list(fnscale=-1)) for maximization
# Example
func1 <- function(x) x^3 - 5*x^2 + 3 
plot(func1, 1, 10, n=100, xlab="x", ylab="func1", type='l', las=1)

optim(10, func1, lower=1, upper=10)
## Warning in optim(10, func1, lower = 1, upper = 10): bounds can only be used with
## method L-BFGS-B (or Brent)

2 Hypothesis testing

a) Sample mean and variance

Using R, simulate a sample of size 64 from the Normal distribution N(2,1). What is the sample mean for your sample? What is the sample variance?

set.seed(123)
sample <- rnorm(64,2,1)
mean(sample)#sample mean = 2.04
var(sample) #sample variance = 0.80
(1/sqrt(64))^2 #sample variance = 0.156??
## [1] 2.038478
## [1] 0.8032835
## [1] 0.015625

Solution keypoint

b) P-value (compare groups)

Calculate the p-value of the sampled data for the null hypothesis that μ = 0. You can do this with a formula or simulation.

### Method I: Direct calculation of test statistic , then p-value.
## Assume known population variance
teststat <- (mean(sample)-0)/(1/sqrt(64)) #t-statistic
pvalue <- pnorm(-abs(teststat), mean=0, sd=1, lower.tail=T) + 
          pnorm(abs(teststat), mean=0, sd=1, lower.tail=F) #add lower & upper tail p-val tgt
#abs() = getting absolute value that is positive value doesn’t change and negative value 
# converted into positive value.
#p-val = 8.68e-60 < 0.05, reject null hypothesis

## Assume population variance unknown
test <- t.test(sample,mu=0) # Ho: mu=0
pvalue <- test$p.value
#p-val = 9.03e-27 < 0.05, reject null hypothesis

### Method II: Simulate the sampling distribution of "estimate of population mean",
### then check for percentile of observed mean
reference <- rnorm(10000, 0, 1/sqrt(64))
mean(sample) > max(reference) #2.03 > 0.48
# mean(sample) is even larger than max(reference)

### Method III: Simulate samples of size 64 from N(0,1) [the hypothesized distribution of data] 
### and count how often mean is more extreme than the "observed mean"
count <- 0
for (i in 1:1000) {
  hypo <- rnorm(64,0,1)
  if (mean(hypo) >= mean(sample)) count <- count + 1
}
count/1000 #= 0

Solution keypoint

3 Log Likelihood complicated example (allowing for vaccination)

a) Likelihood function

Derive the likelihood function in slides 24

b) Max likelihood

Write the exact and simplified likelihood in R, and obtain the maximum likelihood estimates.

x0 <- 183
x1 <- 147
n0 <- 285200
n1 <- 434900

## full likelihood
full <- function(x){
  lambda0 <- exp(x[1]) #x[1] is beta0; x[2] is beta1
  lambda1 <- exp(x[1]+x[2])

  lik <- dpois(x0,n0*lambda0,1)+dpois(x1,n1*lambda1,1) #2 poisson distribution
  lik #why lamda = exp(beta0) + exp(beta0+beta1)? why 2 distribution add tgt?
}

optim(c(0.1,0.1), full , method="CG", control=list(fnscale=-1))

## simplified likelihood
prop <- function(x){
  beta0 <- x[1]
  beta1 <- x[2]

  lik <- ((x0+x1)*beta0 + x1*beta1)- (n0*exp(beta0) + n1*exp(beta0+beta1))
  return(lik)
}

optim(c(0.1,0.1), prop , method="CG", control=list(fnscale=-1))
